\begin_layout Subsection
Followee Recommendation Algorithm
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Followee-Recommendation-Algorithm"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the context of the Twitter social network, a user has a group of 
\emph on
followees
\emph default
 (outgoing edges) and 
\emph on
followers 
\emph default
(incoming edges).
 The algorithm used as case study, proposed in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Armentano2012"

\end_inset

, can be divided in two stages.
 It first explores the followee/follower network near the target user (i.e.,
 the user receiving the suggestions) to select a set of potential users
 to recommend.
 Then, the candidates are filtered and ranked according to different criteria
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Armentano2011"

\end_inset

, such as the number of common friends with the target user or the matching
 of their content-based profiles.
 In this work we focus on supporting the first stage of the algorithm on
 a large graph, letting aside the quality of the actual recommendation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exploration of the followee/follower network in this algorithm is based
 on the characterization of Twitter users made in several studies
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Java2007,Krishnamurthy2008"

\end_inset

 and the fact that online social networks had become real-time information
 sources and news spreading mediums besides fostering the formation of social
 ties
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kwak2010"

\end_inset

.
 From an information-centric point of view, users are mainly divided in
 two categories: information sources and information seekers.
 Users behaving as information sources tend to collect a large amount of
 followers as they post useful information or news, whereas information
 seekers follow several users to get information but rarely post a tweet
 themselves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rationale behind the graph traversal stage of this algorithm relies
 in the categorization of users as information seekers or information sources.
 Thus, it is assumed that the target user is an information seeker that
 has already identified some interesting Twitter users acting as information
 sources (i.e., his/her followees).
 Other people who also follow these people (i.e.
 followers of the user followees) is likely to share some interests with
 the target user and might have discovered other relevant information sources
 on the same topics (i.e., their followees).
 This last group is then composed of potential candidates for suggesting
 to the user as future followees.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More formally, the search of candidate users is performed according to the
 following steps:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Step
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

1.
 Starting with the target user 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{T}$
\end_inset

 (an information seeker), obtain the list of users he/she follows into a
 list 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\left\{ s_{1},s_{2},\text{â€¦},s_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Members of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 are likely to be information sources.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Step
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

2.
 For each element in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, obtain its followers.
 Let us call the union of all these lists 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $L={\displaystyle \bigcup_{\forall s\in followees\left(u_{T}\right)}followers\left(s\right)}$
\end_inset

.
 Members of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 are likely to be information seekers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Step
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

3.
 For each element in 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 obtain its followees.
 Let us call the union of all these lists 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $T={\displaystyle \bigcup_{\forall l\in L}followees\left(l\right)}$
\end_inset

.
 Members of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 are likely to be information sources.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Step
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

4.
 Exclude from 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 those users who the user being recommended is already following.
 Let us call the resulting list of candidates
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

